# DateMatch ‚Äî Dating App Match Outcome Predictor

Predicts one of **10 match outcomes** from dating profile behaviour signals using a
**Gradient Boosting** model (60.32% accuracy).

## Project layout

```
datematch/
‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ backend/
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ app.py              ‚Üê Flask API (2 endpoints)
‚îÇ   ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ requirements.txt
‚îÇ   ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ models/             ‚Üê place all .pkl files here
‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ best_model.pkl
‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ label_encoders.pkl
‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ le_target.pkl
‚îÇ       ‚îú‚îÄ‚îÄ scaler.pkl
‚îÇ       ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ scaler2.pkl
‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ frontend/
    ‚îî‚îÄ‚îÄ index.html          ‚Üê open directly in a browser
```

## Quick start

### 1 ¬∑ Backend

```bash
cd backend

# (recommended) create a virtual environment
python -m venv .venv
Set-ExecutionPolicy -ExecutionPolicy RemoteSigned -Scope Process
.venv\Scripts\activate


# install dependencies ‚Äî scikit-learn version must match the trained models
pip install -r requirement.txt --quiet

# start the API
python app.py
# ‚Üí http://localhost:5000
```

### 2 ¬∑ Frontend

Just open `frontend/index.html` in your browser ‚Äî no build step needed.

When the page loads it calls `GET /metadata` to populate the dropdowns.
If the backend is offline it falls back to hard-coded options so you can still
see the UI.

---

## API reference

### `GET /metadata`
Returns dropdown options and feature metadata.

```json
{
  "categorical_options": {
    "gender": ["Female", "Genderfluid", ...],
    ...
  },
  "outcome_classes": ["Blocked", "Catfished", ...],
  "numeric_features": ["app_usage_time_min", ...],
  "feature_order": [...]
}
```

### `POST /predict`
Body (JSON) ‚Äî all 15 features required:

```json
{
  "gender": "Male",
  "sexual_orientation": "Straight",
  "location_type": "Urban",
  "income_bracket": "High",
  "education_level": "Bachelor\u2019s",
  "app_usage_time_min": 90,
  "swipe_right_ratio": 0.6,
  "likes_received": 173,
  "mutual_matches": 23,
  "profile_pics_count": 4,
  "bio_length": 150,
  "message_sent_count": 75,
  "emoji_usage_rate": 0.36,
  "last_active_hour": 13,
  "swipe_time_of_day": "Early Morning"
}
```

Response:

```json
{
  "prediction": "Mutual Match",
  "confidence": 0.4231,
  "probabilities": {
    "Blocked": 0.031,
    "Catfished": 0.018,
    "Chat Ignored": 0.112,
    "Date Happened": 0.095,
    "Ghosted": 0.074,
    "Instant Match": 0.089,
    "Mutual Match": 0.423,
    "No Action": 0.064,
    "One-sided Like": 0.057,
    "Relationship Formed": 0.037
  }
}
```

---

## Pipeline notes (mirrors the notebook)

| Step | Artifact | Applied to |
|------|----------|------------|
| 1 | `label_encoders.pkl` (one `LabelEncoder` per column) | `gender`, `sexual_orientation`, `location_type`, `income_bracket`, `education_level`, `swipe_time_of_day` |
| 2 | `scaler.pkl` (`StandardScaler`) | all 15 features after encoding |
| 3 | `best_model.pkl` (`GradientBoostingClassifier`) | scaled feature vector |
| 4 | `le_target.pkl` (`LabelEncoder`) | inverse-transform predicted int ‚Üí label |

**‚öÝ Note on apostrophes**: The education-level classes were trained with curly
apostrophes (`'`). The backend normalises any straight apostrophe (`'`) input
automatically, so the frontend can use either style.

**sklearn version**: The models were serialised with scikit-learn **1.6.1**.
Pin your environment to that version (see `requirements.txt`) to avoid
`InconsistentVersionWarning` and potential prediction drift.